@node not01 "VOYAGER 3 NEWS"
                                 VOYAGER 3 NEWS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: Oliver 'owagner' Wagner

The mysterious message from the 14th and the general silence regarding V3
although I kind-of announced a V3.3 warrants a explanation.

Nope, it's not Alina keeping me from work, or me and Claudi trying to setup
another baby.

What has happened -- and still is happening -- is that V3 got a complete new
layout engine, written from scratch.

This originated in a discussion I had with Jon 'Sircus' Bright of Silicon
Circus, in which I was constantly moaning about how horrible the current layout
implementation in V3 would be, how hard it is to locate and fix even minor
quirks, and how good it would be to rewrite it from scratch, doing it all much
better, based on the know-how gained with the current implementation.

He generally just kept saying "Why don't you do it, then?", and, after I spent
several hours finding and eliminating a quirk related to table cell borders, it
finally sank in, and I bagan to ditch the old implementation.

There are several reasons why the old engine was "bad" from a programmer's point
of view even if it does not look that bad at the user level.

First, it's basic design concept still originated in the flat HTML 2.0 layouting
code which I wrote in early 1995, without any concepts of frames, tables,
Javascript, DHTML or style sheets.

The layouter was completely stateless, and could not do any incremental
processing. That V3 *seems* to be able to layout incrementally is in fact just
careful selection of which areas are rerendered when new data arrives -- the
actual internal representation of the HTML page was always rebuild from scratch.

This is not only slow, but brought in many additional problems with Javascript.
Javascript is a OO language, and does not expect objects to suddenly vanish and
reappear with different memory addresses just because new data from a largish
page arrived. There were many kludges to work around this in the current
release, some of them tend to not work properly.

There was no clear distinction between *parsing* HTML (i.e. reading tags and
creating objects out of them) and *layouting* (placing those objects on screen)
-- it was all done in one place. So, when new data arrived, instead of simply
parsing the new data only, adding it to the existing object tree, and then doing
a layout run, it all had to be done from scratch. The same was true when the
container width of the layout space changed -- in laymen terms, when one resized
V's window.

There was also no proper recursive implementation of table layouting. When
hitting a table, V used to parse and layout the underlying HTML code three times
(to get the minimum and maximum sizes, to get the heights, and a final run to
actually create objects of this). This generally does work, but requires 3
complete runs over the contents of a table -- which is bad when the table
contained another table, because then the inner table parsed it's contents 3*3=9
times, and a even more nested tables 3*3*3=27 times... you can probably guess
why V tends to slow down so heavily on deeply nested tables. In the real world,
this was not that bad, because V would have cached min/max sizes of tables and
reuse them properly. However, when carefully "designing" a web page with many
nested tables with unspecified widths, it was possible to effectivly render the
cache useless -- www.freshmeat.net is a good example of this.

All this was known for a long time, and I often had considered to drop this
implementation in favour of a new one. Up to now, however, I always hesitated to
replace this core functionality, out of fear that it would take more time than
what could be justified. Instead, I kept optimizing the underlying primitives of
the parsing/layouting process (HTML tag scanning, text width calculation etc.).

Well, that's all history now.

I've been working on the new code for about a month now, and it's near usability
now.

And what usability -- layout is now blazingly fast (even freshmeat's HTML from
hell goes through in tenth of a second, instead of tens of seconds), resizing
V's window is instantious, a proper OO design of the underlying objects makes
long-missing stuff like <TABLE ALIGN=LEFT|RIGHT> magically work as-is.

I'm going to release a beta as soon as enough of the browsing functionality is
back to warrant a look.

(btw, myvclass.c was the 180kbyte source monster which implemented the old
layouting core. Seeing it being "cvs removed" from the development tree was a
moment of great joy to all of the V developers :-)
